post_text: We are pleased to announce that Goodridge Public School will be providing free breakfast and lunch to all students as of today, due to the government extending the Summer Food Service Program. Meals will be free until December 2020 or until funding runs out (we will notify families when this happens). We will still charge our normal rates for seconds and extra milk. Please continue to fill out Free and Reduced Lunch Applications as many of our funding streams are tied to our Free and Reduced Lunch numbers. Please call the school if you have any questions.

post_text:
The Goodridge Board of Education met on August 11th at 8:00PM in the Community Center and approved Goodridge Public School's Safe, Flexible, and Consistent Learning Plan for the 20-21 School Year.

The Board also established the Base Learning Model to start out the year. Goodridge Public School will be open for: In-Person Learning for All Students, 5 days a week. Family's also have the option of opting to distance learn or opting to start out in a 1 month hybrid learning trial (Monday and Tuesday in school and Wednesday-Friday distance learning). Dismissal time for students was also changed to 3:15 for this school year.

Plans will be mailed out to family's today.

Our Official Start of School Survey will be available tomorrow (Thursday, August 13th). This is a mandatory survey for all family's to inform the school of their final decisions relating to the status of school for their son/daughter, transportation, and meals.

Please do not hesitate to call the school if you have any questions.

post_text: The MSHSL Board of Directors met today. They voted to move volleyball and football to a "fourth season", which would take place between winter (basketball) and spring (track/baseball) sports seasons. As of right now, basketball is still set to begin on time, and will operate as normal. There are not a lot of specifics at this point, but we will pass them along when we know more. Again, Football and Volleyball have been moved to the Spring for the time-being.

post_text:
Good afternoon,

The Governor's mask mandate starts tonight at 11:59pm for all indoor activities. It is in effect until further notice from the Governor.

Staff and students have to wear a mask when indoors (school and activities), except when they are performing tasks that require exertion (breathing hard). There is also an exemption for those who have medical conditions or who cannot handle wearing a mask. These exemptions are spelled out in the Governor's executive order. Please communicate with your son or daughters coach if your son/daughter qualifies for an exemption.

All athletes must bring and wear a mask to practice. They may take it off at practice when directed by their coach if they are going to perform an activity that requires exertion as spelled out in the executive order.

Please let your son or daughters coach know if you need a mask.

Thanks for your help and compliance on this matter.

Let Mr. Lunsetter or Mr. Loberg know if you have any questions.

Grygla School
July 14 at 1:45 PM ·

The Minnesota State High School League board of directors met this morning. The board said that at this time, they are planning on starting fall activities on August 17th as planned. HOWEVER, they are also planning contingency plans that span from having full participation on August 17th all the way to having no fall sports season at all. At this point we are receiving very little guidance about what the fall will look like, not only for sports but for school as well. We will keep everyone updated as soon as we know more details. Thank you for your patience and support in this!

Chargers Parents, check this out!

Minnesota is now offering funds for families of children ages 5 to 18 who qualify for free or reduced-price school meals. The new program, called Pandemic EBT (P-EBT), will provide up to $325 per child that families can use to purchase nutritious food for their household. Approximately 350,000 Minnesota children could benefit.

Learn more at: www.mn.p-ebt.org

post_text:
Charger families receiving meal delivery services: Our staff is following all guidelines to ensure the safety and quality of our meal delivery service. We are doing everything we can to keep our Charger families safe. Here are a few recommendations we have received on things you can do at home:
*Leave the outermost bag on your doorstep to throw away at a later time. Only bring the containers inside.
*Wash hands before transferring food from the to-go containers to your own dishware.
*Hands should be washed again prior to eating.
*Once done eating, all containers and packaging should be disposed of, dishes should be washed, and the table and counters should be cleaned and sanitized.
If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to call us!
text:
Charger families receiving meal delivery services: Our staff is following all guidelines to ensure the safety and quality of our meal delivery service. We are doing everything we can to keep our Charger families safe. Here are a few recommendations we have received on things you can do at home:
*Leave the outermost bag on your doorstep to throw away at a later time. Only bring the containers inside.
*Wash hands before transferring food from the to-go containers to your own dishware.
*Hands should be washed again prior to eating.
*Once done eating, all containers and packaging should be disposed of, dishes should be washed, and the table and counters should be cleaned and sanitized.
If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to call us!

Good afternoon,

We need all our parents to fill out our Mandatory Home Delivery Questionnaire so that we know if you would like deliveries brought to your front door and left in a cooler/box that you provide or left at the end of your driveway in a cooler/box that you provide. post_text: Good morning Chargers! The National Day of Unplugging is here! Students and staff will be volunteering their cell phones before school and will get them back during homeroom today. shared_text:
Goodridge Public School
March 4 at 2:57 PM ·

Hey Charger staff and high school students...are you ready for a challenge? March 6-7 is National Day of Unplugging. We are challenging all staff and high school students to be unplugged for the entire school day on Friday, March 6!

People can turn their cell phones and smart watches in on Friday morning in the lobby. They will be kept in a safe, locked room until the end of the day. Around 3:15, we will begin to give back cell phones to students and staff who participated. We'll also take a picture to share our daring, unplugged Chargers!

We are really excited about this challenge and hope that many people will choose to participate. In fact, we've already had several people commit to unplug! So come on Chargers, we dare you, are you ready to unplug? It will give everybody a chance to live in the moment, focus, see a new perspective, meet and visit with new friends, etc. Will you unplug?!
text:
Goodridge Public School
March 4 at 2:57 PM ·

Hey Charger staff and high school students...are you ready for a challenge? March 6-7 is National Day of Unplugging. We are challenging all staff and high school students to be unplugged for the entire school day on Friday, March 6!

People can turn their cell phones and smart watches in on Friday morning in the lobby. They will be kept in a safe, locked room until the end of the day. Around 3:15, we will begin to give back cell phones to students and staff who participated. We'll also take a picture to share our daring, unplugged Chargers!

We are really excited about this challenge and hope that many people will choose to participate. In fact, we've already had several people commit to unplug! So come on Chargers, we dare you, are you ready to unplug? It will give everybody a chance to live in the moment, focus, see a new perspective, meet and visit with new friends, etc. Will you unplug?!

On December 9 in Goodridge, Prowler Wrestling hosted a Junior Varsity Dual vs. the Bemidji Lumberjacks. Great job to all wrestlers! Here are the results for our two wrestlers from Goodridge:

During the dual, Kehan Nelson won by a fall (pin) & Jolson Sargent lost by decision of 12-10. During the exhibition matches, Kehan Nelson won by major decision of 11-0 & Jolson Sargent lost by a fall (pin).

Thank you to the Prowler coaching staff & volunteers for their help. Also, thank you to the crowd for coming out and supporting our two wrestlers, as well as the Prowler wrestling team!

post_text: The Goodridge School District is seeking quotes for a glass block removal and remodeling project. Project will consist of glass block removal and pertinent demolition, interior remodeling as required, framing and installation of new windows, and siding replacement in the elementary and industrial arts wings. Quotes should include labor and materials and are due by December 13th at noon. Quotes should be mailed to the Goodridge School, PO Box 195, Goodridge, MN 56725, or delivered to the district office. For information contact Russ Bode (218)-378-4134. The district is seeking quotations, not bids, and said quotations will be subject to further negotiation once all quotes are submitted and opened. The district reserves the right to negotiate the quotations, and to award the contract to someone other than the one with the lowest quotation.

post_text:
Check out what Ms. Halvorson has been keeping our 7th grade busy with...

In 7th Grade History we were discussing one of their vocabulary words, petition, and the 7th graders became very excited to exercise the same rights our founding fathers did when they sent the Olive Branch Petition to King George III. They harnessed their enthusiasm and took it upon themselves to create their own petition, asking the school cooks to serve ice cream with their lunches more often. They even went around to other classes to collect signatures for their petition. Yay for active young citizens in the making!

7th Grade also recently did an escape room, or an 'escape tunnel' to be more specific, based on facts from the Revolutionary War. Here's a picture of our winning team who was the first to 'escape'!

post_text:
The history classroom was graffitied by students last week...
with 250+ facts about World War I!!!

We had a special topic segment on WWI this week in honor of Veterans Day being around the corner. The entire high school learned about WWI and each day, each student was asked to write one fact about WWI that they had learned that day, however, it couldn't be a fact that was already listed on our 'graffiti board,' it had to be a new and different fact. The result was whiteboards filled with 250+ facts about WWI that our students learned last week!

post_text: On Wednesday the Junior Class went to go visit NDSU and the Hjemkost Center. Students got to see exhibits on the Hjemkomst Viking ship, the Hopperstad Stave Church, "War, Flu, and Fear", and "America's Monster's, Superheroes, and Villians." The students learned about the Hjemkomst voyage, Vikings, Norwegian conversion to Christianity, the Spanish Influenza, World War I, and how toys reflect our culture's history.
